The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Tuesday, April 27, 2004 				 Govt shield for future Dubeys
 R. VENKATARAMAN																								New Delhi, April 26: The Centre today submitted a resolution to the Supreme Court, saying a law to protect whistle-blowers is ready.																								The Union government told the apex court that the law commissions draft bill  the Public Interest Disclosure and Protection of Informers Bill, 2002  was under its consideration.																								The resolution authorises the Central Vigilance Commission to deal with complaints and protect the identity of informers alleging corruption in government departments until the bill becomes law. 																								The Centres resolution was submitted in the court today which was hearing a public interest litigation in the wake of the Satyendra Dubey murder case. 																								Dubey, a civil engineer from IIT Kanpur, had made corruption allegations in a confidential letter to Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee while working with the Golden Quadrilateral project in Bihar. But the letter was leaked, leading to his murder in November last year, allegedly by the Bihar land mafia.																								Appearing for the Centre, solicitor-general Kirit Raval told a bench of Justices Ruma Pal and P. Venkatarama Reddi that the ministry of personnel had notified a resolution empowering the vigilance commission to receive complaints of corruption in central government agencies.																								According to the resolution, a copy of which was obtained by this newspaper, the commission will be the sole authority and the designated agency to receive written complaints or disclosures on any allegation of corruption or of misuse of office by any employee of the central government or any corporation established by or under any Central Act, government companies, societies or local authorities owned or controlled by the central government. The disclosure or complaint shall contain as full particulars as possible and shall be accompanied by supporting documents or other materials.																								The resolution adds that the commission may, if it deems fit, call for further information or particulars from the persons making the disclosure and if the complaint is anonymous, the designated agency shall not take any action in the matter. 
